metadata.name: Undine
metadata.description:
Undine (from Latin unda â€” "wave") is a mythological humanoid female creature associated with reservoirs, fields and fields. The German-Scandinavian and Baltic analog of the Slavic mermaid, a character of the lower mythology of the peoples of Europe.

Undines are beautiful girls, sometimes with fish tails, who come out of the water and comb their hair, singing and beauty, luring travelers into the depths. They seduce men, because if they give birth to a child from an earthly person, they will be able to find an immortal soul.

Like nymphs and mermaids, undines "rush over fields" According to legends, a person who gets a fern flower will be able to look at undines without hindrance, not succumb to their charm, and even enlist their help in field work, since undines can control the weather by sending rains.

The medieval alchemists called Undines spirits that control the water element
